        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Resolution: The high-angular resolution of 0.12" is needed to resolve the close binary VLA 1A + 1B (within 0.5"), as well as to resolve the accretion disk structures around the individual objects composing the triple sistem (VLA 1A +B and VLA2). 

Sensitivity and Frequency: Dust continuum at the frequency of 350 GHz has been selected given that is at this frequency where we can make the best estimate of resolution and sensitivity for assure detection with ALMA to reach our goals. In fact, previous dust continuum measurements at 345 GHz with 16 arcsec beam toward this triple system show emission with an intensity of 1.2 Jy/beam (Fischer et al. 2010). From this flux density, assuming that the emission comes essentially from a region of 5 arcsec (the size of the expected circummultiple disk), a minimum average continuum flux density of about 0.7 mJy/beam is expected in that region when observed with 0.12" beam (the peak emission will be higher given that the emission is expected to be more concentrated toward VLA 1A+B and VLA 2; in the proposal we have quoted a conservative peak value of 1 mJy/beam). This can be imaged with a S/N ratio &gt; 10 with a sensitivity of 0.07 mJy/beam with one hour of ALMA observations. To have the maximum sensitivity of ALMA we have selected the single continuum mode, dual. The required sensitivity and angular resolution to reach our scientific goals cannot be obtained with any other instrument in the world.</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
